#!/usr/bin/env -S uv run --script
# /// script
# requires-python = ">=3.11"
# dependencies = []
# ///
"""vapic - a capability harness around the official `vapi` CLI.

It resolves a Vapi API key through the capability connection cascade, injects
that key into the child environment, and normally forwards commands verbatim to
`vapi`. vapic owns project policy, connection selection, and readiness. Vapi
owns the actual voice-AI command surface.

USAGE
  vapic <command> [args...]    Forward to `vapi <command> [args...]`, normally
                               with the selected connection injected as
                               VAPI_API_KEY.
  vapic bootstrap [--yes]      Check/install the official Vapi CLI. Without
                               --yes, print the install plan and make no change.
  vapic connections            Where every connection's values resolve from
                               (tier, source, secrets masked). Local only.
  vapic doctor [--connection <id>]
                               Prove the selected Vapi key resolves, the
                               official CLI exists, and the key is accepted.
  vapic help                   Print this contract.

Contract commands (the same on every capability; vapic's own, never forwarded):
  vapic stub                                  One-line awareness text.
  vapic manifest --json                       Machine-readable declaration.
  vapic guide [connections|official-cli]      Guide topics / one guide body.
  vapic ids list|get <l>|set <l> <v>|rm <l>   The project identifiers envelope
        [--note <text>]                       (capabilities/vapic/identifiers.json).
  vapic refs                                  Menu of the project's reference files.

Agent-invoked. Run `vapic help` to reload this contract; run `vapi --help` (the
real CLI) for the full command surface. vapic deliberately does not re-document
or re-map the official Vapi commands.

MODEL
  vapic is not a general REST client for Vapi and not a replacement command
  surface. It is a thin auth shim: it chooses one declared connection, sets
  VAPI_API_KEY plus optional VAPI_ENV, VAPI_API_BASE_URL, and
  VAPI_DASHBOARD_URL, then normally runs the official `vapi` CLI with inherited
  stdio. `vapic --connection staging assistant list` runs `vapi assistant list`
  under the staging key; stdout, stderr, prompts, --json, colors, and exit code
  are Vapi CLI's own unless the documented narrow read-list fallback is
  triggered.

  It REQUIRES a capability connection and never falls back to the official
  `~/.vapi-cli.yaml` login state. That refusal is the scoping guarantee: a
  command can never silently run against whichever Vapi account the human last
  selected with `vapi login` or `vapi auth switch`. Use native `vapi` directly
  for manual login/account management; use vapic for agent work.

  Narrow resilience exception: official Vapi CLI v0.2.1 can fail to decode
  list responses for `assistant list` and `call list` when the API returns
  schema variants its pinned Go SDK cannot unmarshal. Only for those exact read
  commands, and only after that recognized failure, vapic retries the official
  read-only REST endpoint with the already-resolved API key in an in-process
  Authorization header. Native success, unrelated failures, all other reads,
  and every write command stay native.

CONNECTIONS
  Configuration resolves as named connections. With no registry the sole
  connection is `default`: VAPI_API_KEY - a Vapi API key. Because a key chooses
  the Vapi organization/environment the agent can reach, its natural home is the
  consuming project's .env when the project owns that integration.
  Resolved (first non-empty wins):
    1. project env   .env.local then .env, walking up from $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR (else cwd)
    2. user config   $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/vapic/credentials.env (default ~/.config/vapic/)
    3. process env   VAPI_API_KEY (deployed box, or one-shot `VAPI_API_KEY=... vapic ...`)
  There is deliberately no token flag - a secret must not touch argv. One Vapi
  account/environment per connection; projects with prod + staging declare one
  connection per key:
    {
      "default": "production",
      "connections": {
        "production": { "secret_env": "VAPI_PRODUCTION_API_KEY",
                        "environment": "production",
                        "allow_write": false },
        "staging": { "secret_env": "VAPI_STAGING_API_KEY",
                     "environment": "staging",
                     "allow_write": true }
      }
    }
  The registry resolves project envelope first, else the machine-level
  ~/.config/vapic/connections.json; first found wins, never merged.

  Entry fields:
    secret_env        required; env var holding the Vapi API key
    environment       optional; production, staging, development
    api_base_url      optional; explicit VAPI_API_BASE_URL override
    dashboard_url     optional; explicit VAPI_DASHBOARD_URL override
    allow_write       optional; default false

  Selection: --connection <id> (accepted anywhere on the command line; consumed
  by vapic, never forwarded). Unflagged, the registry's "default" pointer
  applies, else the sole entry; several entries without a pointer is refused
  as ambiguous.

WRITE GATE
  Vapi can place outbound calls, change assistants, phone numbers, tools,
  webhooks, campaigns, squads, and billing-relevant resources. Writes therefore
  default to refused. A read-only connection allows only known read/status/help
  commands; unknown official commands require allow_write: true instead of
  being guessed safe.

COMMANDS vapic owns
  connections
      The resolution report - every connection, every value, its winning tier
      and source, secrets masked. Local only: no network, no token use.

  bootstrap [--yes]
      Check whether the official `vapi` CLI is on PATH. Without --yes, emit the
      official install command and exit 0 without changing the machine. With
      --yes, download https://vapi.ai/install.sh to a temporary file and run it.

  doctor [--connection <id>]
      Per connection (every configured one bare; one with --connection): resolve
      its key, confirm `vapi` exists, run the resilient assistant-list probe
      with injected env, and report the selected environment. Exit 0 all healthy /
      2 key missing or rejected / 5 official CLI missing or unreachable.

  help
      Print this document. (`vapi --help` is the real CLI's surface, a separate
      thing; vapic reserves bare `help` for itself but forwards `help <cmd>`.)

EVERYTHING ELSE - forwarded verbatim to `vapi`, key injected, I/O transparent.
  Run `vapi --help` and `vapi <cmd> --help` for the official surface. Common reaches:
    assistant list|get|create|update|delete
    call list|get|create
    phone list|get|create|update|delete
    tool list|get|create|update|delete
    logs
    listen --forward-to <url>

EXIT CODES (vapic's own layer)
  0 success - 2 auth (token missing or rejected) - 4 policy refusal: the
  project gate (capabilities/settings.json) on any verb, or a write verb on a
  read-only connection (allow_write: false); ask the user, never lift a gate
  yourself - 5 environment (vapi not on PATH, installer failed, or unreachable)
  - 6 input (bad use of a vapic-owned command, or an unknown/ambiguous connection).
  Forwarded commands return Vapi CLI's own exit code, not these - except the
  documented read-list fallback, which uses vapic's auth/environment categories
  if the REST retry fails. vapic is transparent for everything it forwards
  (after the gate).

EXAMPLES
  vapic bootstrap
  vapic doctor
  vapic --connection staging assistant list
  vapic --connection staging assistant create --help
  vapic --connection production logs
  VAPI_API_KEY=... vapic assistant list
"""

from __future__ import annotations

import json
import os
import shutil
import subprocess
import sys
from pathlib import Path
from typing import NoReturn

# --- Capability declaration — one home for every contract fact ---------------

NAME = "vapic"
SUMMARY = ("Connection harness around the official `vapi` CLI - resolves a "
           "Vapi API key, injects it, and forwards commands to `vapi` with a "
           "narrow read-list fallback; the command surface is `vapi --help`.")
SCOPE = "project"   # credential scope: "project" | "user"
CRED_KEYS = [
    {"key": "VAPI_API_KEY", "secret": True, "required": True,
     "note": "Vapi API key; lives in the consuming project's .env by default"},
    {"key": "VAPI_ENV", "secret": False, "required": False,
     "note": "official CLI environment: production, staging, or development"},
    {"key": "VAPI_API_BASE_URL", "secret": False, "required": False,
     "note": "optional official CLI API base URL override"},
    {"key": "VAPI_DASHBOARD_URL", "secret": False, "required": False,
     "note": "optional official CLI dashboard URL override"},
]
WRITE_VERBS = {
    "assistant", "call", "phone", "tool", "workflow", "squad", "webhook",
    "campaign", "listen", "init", "auth", "config", "mcp", "update",
}
WRITE_DEFAULT = False   # Vapi writes can call people or mutate paid resources
DOCS_BASE = ("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ai-cluster-one/capabilities/"
             "main/capabilities/vapic/guides/")
TOPICS = ["connections", "official-cli"]
STATE = False       # True when the capability writes session/cache state
POST_INSTALL = [{"cmd": "vapic bootstrap", "note": "check the official Vapi CLI"}]

_CONFIG_HOME = Path(os.environ.get("XDG_CONFIG_HOME") or (Path.home() / ".config"))
CREDENTIALS_ENV = _CONFIG_HOME / "vapic" / "credentials.env"
_STATE_HOME = Path(os.environ.get("XDG_STATE_HOME") or (Path.home() / ".local" / "state"))

TOKEN_NAME = "VAPI_API_KEY"
ENV_NAME = "VAPI_ENV"
API_BASE_NAME = "VAPI_API_BASE_URL"
DASHBOARD_NAME = "VAPI_DASHBOARD_URL"
VAPI_INSTALL_URL = "https://vapi.ai/install.sh"
VAPI_API_BASE_DEFAULT = "https://api.vapi.ai"
VAPI_REST_USER_AGENT = "vapic-capability"
DOCTOR_TIMEOUT = 30.0


# >>> contract: capability core (generated — edit contract/preamble.py, run `capabilities sync-contract`) >>>

# --- Error reporting ---------------------------------------------------------

def _die(exit_code: int, code: str, message: str,
         hint: str | None = None, status: int | None = None) -> NoReturn:
    err: dict = {"code": code, "message": message}
    if hint:
        err["hint"] = hint
    if status is not None:
        err["status"] = status
    sys.stderr.write(json.dumps({"error": err}, ensure_ascii=False) + "\n")
    sys.exit(exit_code)


def _emit(value) -> None:
    if isinstance(value, str):
        sys.stdout.write(value)
        if value and not value.endswith("\n"):
            sys.stdout.write("\n")
    else:
        sys.stdout.write(json.dumps(value, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2) + "\n")


# --- Project / file plumbing -------------------------------------------------

def _parse_env_file(path: Path) -> dict:
    """Parse a KEY=VALUE env/dotenv file. Missing/unreadable file -> {}."""
    out: dict = {}
    try:
        text = path.read_text()
    except OSError:
        return out
    for line in text.splitlines():
        line = line.strip()
        if not line or line.startswith("#") or "=" not in line:
            continue
        k, v = line.split("=", 1)
        k = k.strip()
        if k.startswith("export "):
            k = k[len("export "):].strip()
        out[k] = v.strip().strip('"').strip("'")
    return out


def _project_root() -> Path | None:
    """Nearest project root, walking up from $CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR (else cwd):
    the first directory holding capabilities/, legacy .capabilities/,
    .env(.local), or .git.
    $HOME is never a project root (the machine registry lives there)."""
    start = os.environ.get("CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR") or os.getcwd()
    here = Path(start).resolve()
    home = Path.home().resolve()
    for d in (here, *here.parents):
        if d == home:
            return None
        if ((d / "capabilities" / "settings.json").is_file()
                or (d / ".capabilities").is_dir()
                or (d / ".env").exists()
                or (d / ".env.local").exists() or (d / ".git").is_dir()):
            return d
    return None


def _project_capabilities_dir(root: Path) -> Path:
    """The active project envelope root.

    `capabilities/` is canonical. A legacy `.capabilities/` remains readable
    until `capabilities init` migrates it. If both exist, the canonical tree
    wins once it carries settings.json; otherwise the legacy configured tree
    remains active so merely creating an empty visible directory loses no gate.
    """
    current = root / "capabilities"
    legacy = root / ".capabilities"
    if (current / "settings.json").is_file() or not legacy.is_dir():
        return current
    return legacy


def _project_env() -> dict:
    """Project .env(.local) at the project root. .env.local overrides .env."""
    root = _project_root()
    if root is None:
        return {}
    merged = _parse_env_file(root / ".env")
    merged.update(_parse_env_file(root / ".env.local"))  # .local wins
    return merged


def _auth_context() -> dict | None:
    """Optional runtime authority envelope passed by an ingress/service.

    Absence means the ordinary project gate is the whole policy. Presence means
    a request-scoped authority layer exists and must fail closed before any
    credential or network work happens.
    """
    raw = os.environ.get("CAPABILITIES_AUTH_CONTEXT")
    if not raw:
        return None
    try:
        if raw.lstrip().startswith("{"):
            data = json.loads(raw)
        else:
            data = json.loads(Path(raw).read_text())
    except (OSError, ValueError) as e:
        _die(4, "auth_context_unreadable",
             "runtime authority context could not be read",
             f"{raw}: {e}")
    if not isinstance(data, dict):
        _die(4, "auth_context_invalid",
             "runtime authority context is not an object")
    return data


def _auth_capability_allowed(rule) -> bool:
    if rule is True or rule == "*":
        return True
    if rule in (False, None):
        return False
    if isinstance(rule, dict):
        if rule.get("deny") is True:
            return False
        if rule.get("enabled") is False or rule.get("allow") is False:
            return False
        return True
    return False


def _auth_gate() -> None:
    ctx = _auth_context()
    if ctx is None:
        return
    allowed = ctx.get("allowed_capabilities")
    if allowed is None:
        return
    if allowed is True or allowed == "*":
        return
    if isinstance(allowed, list):
        if NAME in allowed or "*" in allowed:
            return
    elif isinstance(allowed, dict):
        if _auth_capability_allowed(allowed.get(NAME, allowed.get("*"))):
            return
    else:
        _die(4, "auth_context_invalid",
             "runtime authority context has invalid allowed_capabilities")
    source = ctx.get("source") or "runtime"
    role = ctx.get("sender_role") or ctx.get("role") or "unknown"
    chat = ctx.get("chat_id") or "unknown"
    _die(4, "capability_not_authorized",
         f"{NAME} is not authorized for this {source} request",
         f"role={role}; chat_id={chat}; adjust runtime authority policy instead of bypassing the gate")


def _gate() -> None:
    """absent → run; enabled → run; disabled → exit 4. Unreadable never blocks.

    If an ingress supplied CAPABILITIES_AUTH_CONTEXT, that request-scoped gate
    is stricter and also runs here, before credentials or network calls.
    """
    _auth_gate()
    root = _project_root()
    if root is None:
        return
    gate_file = _project_capabilities_dir(root) / "settings.json"
    try:
        entry = json.loads(gate_file.read_text()).get("capabilities", {}).get(NAME)
    except (OSError, ValueError):
        return
    if isinstance(entry, dict) and entry.get("enabled") is False:
        _die(4, "disabled",
             f"{NAME} is disabled in this project ({gate_file})",
             "Do not enable it yourself — ask the user whether to enable it, then stop.")


def _env_dir() -> Path | None:
    """The capability's envelope dir in the project's active capabilities/."""
    root = _project_root()
    return (_project_capabilities_dir(root) / NAME) if root is not None else None


def _state_dir() -> Path:
    """State follows the scope of the credentials that minted it; project state
    lands inside the envelope only where capabilities/ already exists."""
    if SCOPE == "project":
        root = _project_root()
        if root is not None:
            envelope = _project_capabilities_dir(root)
            if (envelope / "settings.json").is_file():
                return envelope / NAME / "state"
    return _STATE_HOME / NAME


# --- Capability contract — the declaration surface --------------------------

def _docs_base() -> str:
    key = f"{NAME.upper()}_DOCS_BASE"
    return (_project_env().get(key)
            or _parse_env_file(CREDENTIALS_ENV).get(key)
            or os.environ.get(key)
            or DOCS_BASE)


def _cmd_guide(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    if not argv:
        _emit(sorted(TOPICS)); return
    topic = argv[0]
    if topic not in TOPICS:
        _die(3, "not_found", f"no guide topic {topic!r}",
             f"topics: {', '.join(sorted(TOPICS)) or 'none shipped'}")
    import urllib.error as _ue
    import urllib.request as _ur
    url = _docs_base().rstrip("/") + "/" + topic + ".md"
    cache_dir = _STATE_HOME / NAME / "guides"
    cache, etag_f = cache_dir / f"{topic}.md", cache_dir / f"{topic}.etag"
    headers = {}
    if cache.exists() and etag_f.exists():
        headers["If-None-Match"] = etag_f.read_text().strip()
    try:
        req = _ur.Request(url, headers=headers)
        with _ur.urlopen(req, timeout=10.0) as resp:
            text = resp.read().decode(resp.headers.get_content_charset() or "utf-8")
            cache_dir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
            cache.write_text(text)
            if resp.headers.get("etag"):
                etag_f.write_text(resp.headers["etag"])
            _emit(text); return
    except _ue.HTTPError as e:
        if e.code == 304 and cache.exists():
            _emit(cache.read_text()); return
        if e.code == 404:
            _die(3, "not_found", f"guide {topic!r} missing upstream", url)
        err = f"upstream returned {e.code}"
    except _ue.URLError as e:
        err = str(e.reason)
    except OSError as e:
        err = str(e)
    if cache.exists():
        sys.stderr.write(json.dumps(
            {"warning": f"upstream unreachable; serving cached copy ({err})"},
            ensure_ascii=False) + "\n")
        _emit(cache.read_text()); return
    _die(5, "network_error", f"could not fetch guide {topic!r}; no cache exists", url)


def _render_ids_markdown(data: dict) -> str:
    """Render the {label: {value, note}} envelope as the labelled markdown
    list the manager's `capabilities ids <NAME>` also produces — one shared
    format across the ids surface and the identifiers section of `help`."""
    lines: list[str] = []
    for label, entry in sorted(data.items()):
        entry = entry if isinstance(entry, dict) else {"value": entry}
        v = entry.get("value")
        vs = f"`{v}`" if isinstance(v, str) else "`" + json.dumps(v, ensure_ascii=False) + "`"
        line = f"- **{label}**: {vs}"
        note = entry.get("note")
        if note:
            line += f" — {note}"
        lines.append(line)
    return "\n".join(lines)


def _identifiers_section() -> str:
    """The Identifiers block appended to the bare top-level help — deterministic
    first-touch surfacing of `capabilities/<NAME>/identifiers.json` so an
    agent following the `<NAME> help` startup protocol loads the discovered
    labels/values/notes into context at once. Empty when no project envelope
    or nothing recorded (do not bloat help with an empty section)."""
    envdir = _env_dir()
    if envdir is None:
        return ""
    ids_file = envdir / "identifiers.json"
    if not ids_file.exists():
        return ""
    try:
        data = json.loads(ids_file.read_text())
    except (OSError, ValueError):
        return ""
    if not isinstance(data, dict) or not data:
        return ""
    header = (
        "\n═══ Identifiers ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n"
        f"Structural lookups discovered for `{NAME}` in this project. Fetch a single\n"
        f"raw value with `{NAME} ids get <label>`; the full envelope is also at\n"
        f"`capabilities ids {NAME}`.\n\n"
    )
    return header + _render_ids_markdown(data) + "\n"


def _cmd_help() -> None:
    """Bare top-level help: the CLI's HELP body (module-level `HELP` if
    defined, else the module docstring), then the project's Identifiers
    section. Only fires when no extra args follow — per-verb help stays
    untouched so `<NAME> help <subcommand>` is not intercepted."""
    g = globals()
    text = g.get("HELP") or g.get("__doc__") or ""
    if text.startswith("\n"):
        text = text.lstrip("\n")
    sys.stdout.write(text)
    if text and not text.endswith("\n"):
        sys.stdout.write("\n")
    section = _identifiers_section()
    if section:
        sys.stdout.write(section)


def _cmd_ids(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    sub = argv[0] if argv else "list"
    envdir = _env_dir()
    ids_file = (envdir / "identifiers.json") if envdir else None
    data: dict = {}
    if ids_file and ids_file.exists():
        try:
            data = json.loads(ids_file.read_text())
        except ValueError:
            _die(6, "bad_envelope", f"{ids_file} is not valid JSON")
    if sub == "list":
        _emit(data); return
    if sub == "get":
        if len(argv) < 2 or argv[1] not in data:
            _die(3, "not_found", "unknown identifier label",
                 f"`{NAME} ids list` shows the labels")
        _emit((data[argv[1]] or {}).get("value")); return
    if sub == "set":
        if len(argv) < 3:
            _die(6, "input", f"usage: {NAME} ids set <label> <value> [--note <text>]")
        if envdir is None or not (envdir.parent / "settings.json").is_file():
            _die(6, "no_envelope", "no capabilities/ envelope in this project",
                 "run `capabilities init` first")
        label, raw = argv[1], argv[2]
        try:
            value = json.loads(raw)
        except ValueError:
            value = raw
        note = ""
        if "--note" in argv:
            ni = argv.index("--note")
            if ni + 1 >= len(argv):
                _die(6, "input", "--note needs a value")
            note = argv[ni + 1]
        data[label] = {"value": value, "note": note or (data.get(label) or {}).get("note", "")}
        envdir.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
        ids_file.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2, sort_keys=True) + "\n")
        _emit({"set": label}); return
    if sub == "rm":
        if len(argv) < 2 or argv[1] not in data:
            _die(3, "not_found", "unknown identifier label",
                 f"`{NAME} ids list` shows the labels")
        del data[argv[1]]
        ids_file.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=2, sort_keys=True) + "\n")
        _emit({"removed": argv[1]}); return
    _die(6, "input", f"unknown ids subcommand {sub!r}", f"{NAME} ids list|get|set|rm")


def _cmd_refs() -> None:
    envdir = _env_dir()
    refdir = (envdir / "reference") if envdir else None
    out = []
    if refdir and refdir.is_dir():
        for md in sorted(refdir.glob("*.md")):
            name = desc = None
            try:
                lines = md.read_text().splitlines()
            except OSError:
                continue
            if lines and lines[0].strip() == "---":
                for line in lines[1:30]:
                    if line.strip() == "---":
                        break
                    if line.startswith("name:"):
                        name = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
                    elif line.startswith("description:"):
                        desc = line.split(":", 1)[1].strip()
            if name:
                out.append({"name": name, "description": desc or "", "path": str(md)})
    _emit(out)


def _contract(argv: list[str]) -> None:
    """Dispatch the contract verbs; domain verbs fall through to the CLI's own
    parser. Runs after _gate(), before any credential is resolved.

    `help` is a contract verb only when bare (no extra args) — the top-level
    dump plus the Identifiers section. `<NAME> help <subcommand>` falls
    through to the CLI so per-verb help stays clean."""
    cmd = argv[0] if argv else ""
    if cmd == "stub":
        _emit(f"{SUMMARY} Run `{NAME} help`.")
    elif cmd == "manifest":
        _emit({"name": NAME, "summary": SUMMARY,
               "credentials": {"scope": SCOPE, "keys": CRED_KEYS},
               "docs": {"base": DOCS_BASE, "topics": sorted(TOPICS)},
               "state": STATE, "post_install": POST_INSTALL})
    elif cmd == "guide":
        _cmd_guide(argv[1:])
    elif cmd == "ids":
        _cmd_ids(argv[1:])
    elif cmd == "refs":
        _cmd_refs()
    elif cmd == "connections":
        _cmd_connections()
    elif cmd == "help" and len(argv) == 1:
        _cmd_help()
    else:
        return
    sys.exit(0)

# <<< contract: capability core <<<


# >>> contract: connections (generated — edit contract/preamble.py, run `capabilities sync-contract`) >>>

def _resolve_env_key(key: str) -> tuple[str | None, str | None, Path | None]:
    """Resolve one env key through cascade tiers 2-4: project .env(.local) →
    user credentials.env → process env. Returns (value, tier, source)."""
    root = _project_root()
    if root is not None:
        for fname in (".env.local", ".env"):
            val = _parse_env_file(root / fname).get(key)
            if val:
                return val, "project", root / fname
    val = _parse_env_file(CREDENTIALS_ENV).get(key)
    if val:
        return val, "user", CREDENTIALS_ENV
    val = os.environ.get(key)
    if val:
        return val, "env", None
    return None, None, None


def _mask(value: str) -> str:
    return ("…" + value[-4:]) if len(value) >= 8 else "****"


def _connections_registry() -> tuple[dict | None, Path | None]:
    """The connections envelope and its path: project envelope first, else the
    user config home. First found wins, never merged; (None, None) when neither
    declares one (the implicit default connection applies)."""
    envdir = _env_dir()
    candidates = ([envdir / "connections.json"] if envdir else []) + \
                 [_CONFIG_HOME / NAME / "connections.json"]
    for reg_file in candidates:
        if not reg_file.is_file():
            continue
        try:
            raw = json.loads(reg_file.read_text())
        except (ValueError, OSError) as e:
            _die(6, "bad_config", f"cannot read {reg_file}: {e}")
        if not isinstance(raw, dict) or not isinstance(raw.get("connections"), dict) \
                or not raw["connections"]:
            _die(6, "bad_config", f"{reg_file} is not a connections envelope",
                 'expected {"default": "<id>", "connections": { ... }}')
        return raw, reg_file
    return None, None


def _select_connection(reg: dict | None, wanted: str | None) -> tuple[str, dict | None]:
    """flag → default pointer → sole entry → die 6. No registry → the implicit
    default. A connection's own `address` field selects it too (used where a
    connection carries a human-recognizable address; absent fields never match)."""
    if reg is None:
        if wanted and wanted != "default":
            _die(6, "unknown_connection",
                 "no connections registry; the sole connection is 'default'",
                 "the implicit default resolves from the credential cascade")
        return "default", None
    conns = reg["connections"]
    if wanted:
        if wanted in conns:
            return wanted, conns[wanted]
        for cid, entry in conns.items():
            if (entry or {}).get("address", "").lower() == wanted.lower():
                return cid, entry
        _die(6, "unknown_connection", f"no connection matches {wanted!r}",
             f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")
    default = reg.get("default")
    if default:
        if default not in conns:
            _die(6, "bad_default", f"default points to unknown connection {default!r}",
                 f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")
        return default, conns[default]
    if len(conns) == 1:
        cid = next(iter(conns))
        return cid, conns[cid]
    _die(6, "ambiguous_connection",
         f"registry defines {len(conns)} connections and no default; "
         f"pass --connection <id>",
         f"known: {', '.join(conns)}")


def _write_gate(conn_id: str, allow_write: bool, verb: str) -> None:
    """Policy from the committed registry; nothing in the cascade lifts it."""
    if verb in WRITE_VERBS and not allow_write:
        _die(4, "read_only",
             f"connection {conn_id!r} does not allow writes",
             "Do not lift the gate yourself — ask the user; granting is "
             "`allow_write: true` on this connection in connections.json.")


def _key_report(key: str, secret: bool, required: bool,
                value: str | None, tier: str | None, source) -> dict:
    return {"key": key, "secret": secret, "required": required,
            "set": bool(value), "tier": tier if value else None,
            "source": str(source) if (value and source) else None,
            "value": (_mask(value) if secret else value) if value else None}


def _missing_required(keys: list) -> list:
    """Required report rows (from _key_report) that did not resolve through the
    cascade — empty ⇒ credentials present. The primitive behind doctor's
    network-free readiness gate, read from the same per-key resolution
    `connections` reports, so the gate and the report can never disagree."""
    return [k["key"] for k in keys if k["required"] and not k["set"]]


def _doctor_gate(report: dict, wanted: str | None) -> None:
    """doctor's network-free readiness gate. Refuse with exit 2 — naming the
    unresolved required keys, before any round-trip — when a connection under
    test cannot resolve its required config through the cascade, so readiness is
    judged by the same resolution `connections` reports, never a parallel check.
    Checks the selected connection, else every connection in the report."""
    conns = report.get("connections") or {}
    targets = [wanted] if (wanted and wanted in conns) else list(conns)
    problems: dict = {}
    for cid in targets:
        miss = _missing_required((conns.get(cid) or {}).get("keys") or [])
        if miss:
            problems[cid] = miss
    if problems:
        detail = "; ".join(f"{c}: {', '.join(ks)}" for c, ks in sorted(problems.items()))
        _die(2, "credentials_missing",
             f"unresolved required config — {detail}",
             f"set each in the project .env/.env.local, the user credentials.env, "
             f"or process env; `{NAME} connections` shows where every value resolves")

# <<< contract: connections <<<


# -- credentials (cascade: project .env(.local) -> user config -> process env) --
# Secrets omit a flag tier: a Vapi API key must not touch argv.

# --- Connections (capability-specific) --------------------------------------

def _literal_report(key: str, value, reg_path: Path | None,
                    required: bool = False) -> dict:
    return _key_report(key, False, required,
                       str(value) if value not in (None, "") else None,
                       "connection" if value not in (None, "") else None,
                       reg_path)


def _connections_report() -> dict:
    """Every connection, every value, its winning tier and source. Local only."""
    reg, reg_path = _connections_registry()
    report: dict = {"default": None, "connections": {}}
    if reg is None:
        keys = []
        for k in CRED_KEYS:
            value, tier, source = _resolve_env_key(k["key"])
            keys.append(_key_report(k["key"], k["secret"], k["required"],
                                    value, tier, source))
        report["default"] = "default"
        report["connections"]["default"] = {"allow_write": WRITE_DEFAULT, "keys": keys}
        return report
    conns = reg["connections"]
    report["default"] = reg.get("default") or \
        (next(iter(conns)) if len(conns) == 1 else None)
    for cid, entry in conns.items():
        entry = entry if isinstance(entry, dict) else {}
        keys = []
        secret_env = entry.get("secret_env")
        if secret_env:
            value, tier, source = _resolve_env_key(secret_env)
            keys.append(_key_report(secret_env, True, True, value, tier, source))
        else:
            keys.append(_key_report("secret_env", False, True, None, None, None))
        for key, field in (
                (ENV_NAME, "environment"),
                (API_BASE_NAME, "api_base_url"),
                (DASHBOARD_NAME, "dashboard_url")):
            if field in entry:
                keys.append(_literal_report(field, entry.get(field), reg_path))
            else:
                value, tier, source = _resolve_env_key(key)
                keys.append(_key_report(key, False, False, value, tier, source))
        report["connections"][cid] = {
            "allow_write": bool(entry.get("allow_write", WRITE_DEFAULT)),
            "keys": keys}
    return report


def _cmd_connections() -> None:
    _emit(_connections_report())


def _build_cfg(cid: str, entry: dict | None) -> tuple[dict | None, dict | None]:
    """Materialize one connection without dying, so doctor can cover all."""
    if entry is None:
        token = _resolve_env_key(TOKEN_NAME)[0]
        if not token:
            return None, {
                "exit": 2, "code": "missing_credentials",
                "message": f"{TOKEN_NAME} is required for vapic",
                "hint": f"set {TOKEN_NAME} in this project's .env(.local), "
                        f"{CREDENTIALS_ENV}, or process env; `vapic guide "
                        f"connections` shows the connection shape"}
        return {
            "id": cid,
            "allow_write": WRITE_DEFAULT,
            "token": token,
            "environment": _resolve_env_key(ENV_NAME)[0],
            "api_base_url": _resolve_env_key(API_BASE_NAME)[0],
            "dashboard_url": _resolve_env_key(DASHBOARD_NAME)[0],
        }, None
    secret_env = entry.get("secret_env")
    if not secret_env:
        return None, {"exit": 6, "code": "no_secret_env",
                      "message": f"connection {cid!r} is missing 'secret_env'"}
    token = _resolve_env_key(secret_env)[0]
    if not token:
        return None, {
            "exit": 2, "code": "missing_secret",
            "message": f"env var {secret_env} (for connection {cid!r}) is unset",
            "hint": f"set {secret_env} in the project's .env / .env.local "
                    f"or the environment"}
    return {
        "id": cid,
        "allow_write": bool(entry.get("allow_write", WRITE_DEFAULT)),
        "token": token,
        "environment": entry.get("environment") or _resolve_env_key(ENV_NAME)[0],
        "api_base_url": entry.get("api_base_url") or _resolve_env_key(API_BASE_NAME)[0],
        "dashboard_url": entry.get("dashboard_url") or _resolve_env_key(DASHBOARD_NAME)[0],
    }, None


# -- vapi invocation ---------------------------------------------------------

def _child_env(cfg: dict | None) -> dict:
    env = dict(os.environ)
    if cfg:
        env[TOKEN_NAME] = cfg["token"]
        if cfg.get("environment"):
            env[ENV_NAME] = str(cfg["environment"])
        if cfg.get("api_base_url"):
            env[API_BASE_NAME] = str(cfg["api_base_url"])
        if cfg.get("dashboard_url"):
            env[DASHBOARD_NAME] = str(cfg["dashboard_url"])
    return env


def _vapi_path() -> str | None:
    return shutil.which("vapi")


def _official_install_command() -> str:
    return f"curl -sSL {VAPI_INSTALL_URL} | bash"


def cmd_bootstrap(args: list[str]) -> None:
    yes = False
    for arg in args:
        if arg == "--yes":
            yes = True
        else:
            _die(6, "input", f"unknown bootstrap argument {arg!r}",
                 "usage: vapic bootstrap [--yes]")
    path = _vapi_path()
    if path:
        _emit({"ok": True, "installed": True, "path": path})
        return
    payload = {
        "ok": not yes,
        "installed": False,
        "install": {"command": _official_install_command(),
                    "url": VAPI_INSTALL_URL},
    }
    if not yes:
        payload["next"] = "run `vapic bootstrap --yes` to execute the official installer"
        _emit(payload)
        return

    import tempfile
    import urllib.request
    try:
        with urllib.request.urlopen(VAPI_INSTALL_URL, timeout=30.0) as resp:
            script = resp.read()
    except OSError as e:
        _die(5, "installer_fetch_failed",
             f"could not fetch official Vapi installer: {e}",
             VAPI_INSTALL_URL)
    tmp_path = None
    try:
        with tempfile.NamedTemporaryFile("wb", delete=False) as tmp:
            tmp.write(script)
            tmp_path = tmp.name
        proc = subprocess.run(["bash", tmp_path], text=True)
    finally:
        if tmp_path:
            try:
                Path(tmp_path).unlink()
            except OSError:
                pass
    if proc.returncode != 0:
        _die(5, "installer_failed",
             f"official Vapi installer exited with {proc.returncode}")
    path = _vapi_path()
    if not path:
        _die(5, "vapi_not_on_path",
             "official Vapi installer completed, but `vapi` is not on PATH",
             "open a new shell or add the install directory to PATH, then rerun `vapic doctor`")
    _emit({"ok": True, "installed": True, "path": path})


def _is_native_help(argv: list[str]) -> bool:
    if not argv:
        return True
    if argv[0] in ("help", "-h", "--help", "version", "--version", "completion", "manual"):
        return True
    return "-h" in argv or "--help" in argv


def _first_word(args: list[str]) -> str | None:
    for arg in args:
        if not arg.startswith("-"):
            return arg
    return None


def _requires_write(argv: list[str]) -> bool:
    if not argv or _is_native_help(argv):
        return False
    root = argv[0]
    if root == "logs":
        return False
    if root == "auth":
        return (_first_word(argv[1:]) or "status") not in {"status", "whoami"}
    if root in {"assistant", "call", "phone", "tool", "workflow",
                "squad", "webhook", "campaign"}:
        return (_first_word(argv[1:]) or "list") not in {
            "list", "get", "show", "status", "describe"}
    return True


def _write_gate_command(conn_id: str, allow_write: bool, argv: list[str]) -> None:
    if not allow_write and _requires_write(argv):
        shown = " ".join(argv[:3]) if argv else "<empty>"
        _die(4, "read_only",
             f"connection {conn_id!r} does not allow writes; `{shown}` is not a known read-only Vapi command",
             "Do not lift the gate yourself - ask the user; granting is "
             "`allow_write: true` on this connection in connections.json.")


def _check_connection(cfg: dict) -> dict:
    """Use a cheap official-CLI read to prove the key is accepted."""
    if not _vapi_path():
        return {"ok": False, "category": 5,
                "error": "the official `vapi` CLI is not on PATH",
                "hint": "run `vapic bootstrap` for the install command"}
    res = _run_resilient_read(["assistant", "list"], cfg, timeout=DOCTOR_TIMEOUT)
    if not res.get("ok"):
        out = {"ok": False, "category": res.get("category") or 5,
               "error": res.get("error") or "`vapi assistant list` failed"}
        if res.get("hint"):
            out["hint"] = res["hint"]
        return out
    return {
        "ok": True,
        "environment": cfg.get("environment") or "production",
        "api_base_url": cfg.get("api_base_url"),
        "dashboard_url": cfg.get("dashboard_url"),
        "probe": res["probe"],
    }


def cmd_doctor(reg: dict | None, wanted: str | None) -> None:
    _doctor_gate(_connections_report(), wanted)
    if wanted is not None or reg is None:
        targets = [_select_connection(reg, wanted)]
    else:
        targets = list(reg["connections"].items())
    connections: dict = {}
    fail_exit = 0
    for cid, entry in targets:
        cfg, problem = _build_cfg(cid, entry)
        if problem:
            res = {"ok": False, "category": problem["exit"],
                   "error": problem["message"]}
            if problem.get("hint"):
                res["hint"] = problem["hint"]
        else:
            res = _check_connection(cfg)
        if not res.get("ok") and not fail_exit:
            fail_exit = res.get("category") or 5
        res.pop("category", None)
        connections[cid] = res
    _emit({"ok": fail_exit == 0, "connections": connections})
    if fail_exit:
        sys.exit(fail_exit)


def _read_fallback_resource(argv: list[str]) -> str | None:
    if argv == ["assistant", "list"]:
        return "assistant"
    if argv == ["call", "list"]:
        return "call"
    return None


def _recognized_vapi_decode_failure(text: str) -> bool:
    low = text.lower()
    if "cannot unmarshal" in low and ("json" in low or "go struct" in low):
        return True
    return "deserializ" in low and ("json" in low or "unmarshal" in low)


def _rest_url(cfg: dict, resource: str) -> str:
    base = str(cfg.get("api_base_url") or VAPI_API_BASE_DEFAULT).rstrip("/")
    return f"{base}/{resource}"


def _rest_read(resource: str, cfg: dict) -> dict:
    import urllib.error
    import urllib.request

    req = urllib.request.Request(
        _rest_url(cfg, resource),
        headers={
            "Authorization": f"Bearer {cfg['token']}",
            "Accept": "application/json",
            "User-Agent": VAPI_REST_USER_AGENT,
        },
        method="GET",
    )
    try:
        with urllib.request.urlopen(req, timeout=DOCTOR_TIMEOUT) as resp:
            text = resp.read().decode(
                resp.headers.get_content_charset() or "utf-8", errors="replace")
            return {"ok": True, "text": text, "probe": f"GET /{resource}"}
    except urllib.error.HTTPError as e:
        if e.code in (401, 403):
            return {"ok": False, "category": 2,
                    "code": "auth_failed",
                    "error": f"Vapi REST fallback returned HTTP {e.code}",
                    "hint": "the key is missing, invalid, revoked, or for the wrong environment"}
        return {"ok": False, "category": 5,
                "code": "rest_http_error",
                "error": f"Vapi REST fallback returned HTTP {e.code}"}
    except (urllib.error.URLError, OSError) as e:
        return {"ok": False, "category": 5,
                "code": "rest_network_error",
                "error": f"Vapi REST fallback could not reach the API: {e}"}


def _native_auth_failure(text: str) -> bool:
    low = text.lower()
    return any(s in low for s in ("api key", "auth", "unauthor", "forbidden", "login"))


def _run_resilient_read(argv: list[str], cfg: dict, timeout: float | None = None) -> dict:
    resource = _read_fallback_resource(argv)
    try:
        proc = subprocess.run(["vapi", *argv],
                              env=_child_env(cfg),
                              capture_output=True, text=True, timeout=timeout)
    except subprocess.TimeoutExpired:
        return {"ok": False, "category": 5,
                "error": f"vapi was unresponsive (`{' '.join(argv)}` timed out)"}
    except OSError as e:
        return {"ok": False, "category": 5, "error": f"could not run vapi: {e}"}
    if proc.returncode == 0:
        return {"ok": True, "stdout": proc.stdout, "stderr": proc.stderr,
                "returncode": 0, "probe": f"vapi {' '.join(argv)}"}

    err = (proc.stderr or proc.stdout or "").strip()
    if resource and _recognized_vapi_decode_failure(err):
        fallback = _rest_read(resource, cfg)
        if fallback.get("ok"):
            fallback["probe"] = f"{fallback['probe']} after vapi {' '.join(argv)} decode fallback"
        return fallback
    if _native_auth_failure(err):
        return {"ok": False, "category": 2,
                "error": err or "Vapi rejected the API key",
                "hint": "the key is missing, invalid, revoked, or for the wrong environment",
                "stdout": proc.stdout, "stderr": proc.stderr,
                "returncode": proc.returncode}
    return {"ok": False, "category": 5,
            "error": err or f"`vapi {' '.join(argv)}` failed",
            "stdout": proc.stdout, "stderr": proc.stderr,
            "returncode": proc.returncode}


def _forward(argv: list[str], cfg: dict | None) -> NoReturn:
    if cfg and _read_fallback_resource(argv):
        res = _run_resilient_read(argv, cfg)
        if res.get("ok"):
            if "text" in res:
                sys.stdout.write(res["text"])
                if res["text"] and not res["text"].endswith("\n"):
                    sys.stdout.write("\n")
            else:
                sys.stdout.write(res.get("stdout") or "")
                sys.stderr.write(res.get("stderr") or "")
            sys.exit(0)
        if "returncode" in res:
            sys.stdout.write(res.get("stdout") or "")
            sys.stderr.write(res.get("stderr") or "")
            sys.exit(int(res["returncode"]))
        _die(int(res.get("category") or 5), res.get("code") or "vapi_read_failed",
             res.get("error") or "Vapi read failed", res.get("hint"))
    try:
        proc = subprocess.run(["vapi", *argv], env=_child_env(cfg))
    except OSError as e:
        _die(5, "vapi_exec_failed", f"could not run vapi: {e}",
             "run `vapic bootstrap` for the install command")
    sys.exit(proc.returncode)


# -- dispatch ----------------------------------------------------------------

def main() -> None:
    _gate()

    argv = sys.argv[1:]
    wanted_conn: str | None = None
    cleaned: list[str] = []
    i = 0
    while i < len(argv):
        a = argv[i]
        if a == "--connection" and i + 1 < len(argv):
            wanted_conn = argv[i + 1]; i += 2; continue
        if a.startswith("--connection="):
            wanted_conn = a.split("=", 1)[1]; i += 1; continue
        cleaned.append(a); i += 1

    _contract(cleaned)
    if not cleaned or (len(cleaned) == 1 and cleaned[0] in ("help", "-h", "--help")):
        sys.stdout.write((__doc__ or "").lstrip("\n"))
        return

    reg, _ = _connections_registry()
    if cleaned[0] == "bootstrap":
        cmd_bootstrap(cleaned[1:])
        return
    if cleaned[0] == "doctor":
        cmd_doctor(reg, wanted_conn)
        return

    if _is_native_help(cleaned):
        if not _vapi_path():
            _die(5, "vapi_not_found", "the official `vapi` CLI is not on PATH",
                 "run `vapic bootstrap` for the install command")
        _forward(cleaned, None)

    cid, entry = _select_connection(reg, wanted_conn)
    allow_write = WRITE_DEFAULT if entry is None else \
        bool(entry.get("allow_write", WRITE_DEFAULT))
    _write_gate_command(cid, allow_write, cleaned)

    cfg, problem = _build_cfg(cid, entry)
    if problem:
        _die(problem["exit"], problem["code"], problem["message"],
             problem.get("hint"))

    if not _vapi_path():
        _die(5, "vapi_not_found", "the official `vapi` CLI is not on PATH",
             "run `vapic bootstrap` for the install command")

    _forward(cleaned, cfg)


if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
